Adult male.description: Canada Warblers have an unstreaked gray back and clean gray wings without wingbars, while Magnolia Warblers have a black or streaked back and obvious wingbars.

Adult female/immature male.description: Female and immature Canada Warblers do not have wingbars, while immature Magnolia Warblers do.

Adult male.description: Prairie Warblers have a yellow head while Magnolia Warblers have a gray head.

Female/immature.description: Female and immature Prairie Warblers have streaked sides that immature Magnolia Warblers lack.

Male.description: Kirtland's Warblers lack the Magnolia Warbler's necklace of black stripes. They also do not have well-defined wingbars like Magnolias. Kirtland's has a very restricted breeding range.

Female.description: Female Kirtland's have a spotted belly and lack the necklaced look of Magnolia Warblers. They also lack well-defined wingbars.

Adult male.description: Nashville Warblers are similar to immature Magnolia Warblers, but lack wingbars and Magnolia's distinctive white-and-black tail pattern.

Female/immature.description: Nashville Warblers are similar to immature Magnolia Warblers, but lack wingbars and Magnolia's distinctive white-and-black tail pattern.
